Linear Regresison Learning¶

A cost function determines how much error exists in a model. This allows us to then adjust the parameters (Intercept and Coefficient).

In Linear Regression, Mean Squared Error (MSE) cost function is used, which is the average of squared error that occurred between the predicted values and actual values.

By simple linear equation y=mx+b we can calculate MSE as (Where: y = actual values, yi = predicted values):

In [5]:
from IPython.display import Image
Image("mse.png", width = 900, height = 450)
Out[5]:

If the intercept and coefficient values were randomly/iteratively adjusted, this would take significant time (if even possible), thus the solution is a technique called Gradient Descent.

Linear Regression - Once Trained¶

  • Each independant attribute has an equation
  • Each has the same intercept
  • This is called multiple regression

K Nearest Neighbour¶

p : int, default=2
Power parameter for the Minkowski metric.

  • When p = 1, this is equivalent to using manhattan_distance
  • When p = 2, this is equivalent to using euclidean_distance

Elbow Method for Selection of K:¶

In [20]:
# elbow method
accValues = []  
for k in range(1,len(attributes),2): 
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    model.fit(attributes, classValues)
    results = model.score(attributes, classValues)
    accValues.append(results.mean())

plt.plot(list(range(1,len(attributes),2)),accValues) 
plt.xlabel('Values of K') 
plt.ylabel('Accuracy') 
plt.title('The Elbow Method') 
plt.show()

naive Bayes in more detail:¶

Naive Bayes is a probalistic classifier

Nave Bayes is a non-parametric probabilistic model based on an assumption of conditional independence among variable attributes. Although this assumption is often violated, nave Bayes classifiers have been shown to work surprisingly well and have highly competitive prediction performance even when compared with some state-of-the art classifiers.

The following formula represents naive bayes, where the c = class that you are calculating for the probability of (note, in SKLEARN, you are returned the proabilities of both classes using: model.predict_proba), x is the probability of that attribute value resulting in a class label.

Decision Trees in more detail:¶

Decision Trees use (typically) the CART algorithm to split the nodes based on each nodes impurity (the lack of homogeneity for a class value - where 1 is the lowest homogeneity and 0 being teh highest - all one class value).

Cart ues Gini impurity, and only works for classification problems. Gini is used over entropy as it does not include a log fucntion (less computationally intensive).

Splitting the tree¶

  • For each split in the attribute values individually calculate the Gini Impurity attribute value to the class value
  • Calculate the Gini Impurity of each split as the weighted average Gini Impurity of child nodes
  • Select the split with the lowest value of Gini Impurity
  • Interatively repeat until you achieve homogeneous nodes only

Please note:¶

SKLEARN's is developed to only work with numerical attributes, and somewhat disguises categorogical features using (what we did - label encorders). Thus the algorithm employs a binary tree approach (ignoring our theoritical example above using Gini), as it is more difficult to identify more that two ranges in a numerical range.

Artificial neural networks in more detail:¶

Neural networks are built of multipe perceptrons, that in essence were developed to mimick (to the most basic sense) a human neuron. The fundamental process of a prediction, is that the inputs $X_1$ to $X_4$ for the play tennis example. For a neural network all of the attribute values need to be numeric.

Next the attributes in a since instance are then multiplied by corrosponding weights, $W_1j$ to $W_4j$ in this example.

Then, the result of each multiplication is summated (called the transfer function).

Then the output of the transfer, is passed through the activation function (in some cases there is a treshold value, but we can ignore for now).

The output of this perceptron can either be the resulting prediction, or feed into another perceptron, creating the network.

Neural Network Learning¶

Essentially, all that is changed is the weights (altough there are several hyperperameters that help with the learning process), and just like in Linear Regression and Logistic Regression, gradient descent is used, to find the optimum weights. The weihgts are selected as random values, and then iteratively changed using gradient descent to find a heuristic solution.
